Cool â€” I poked around and found useful things from AutoGen and LangChain that we can steal/adapt for our own multi-agent sandbox. Hereâ€™s whatâ€™s good, whatâ€™s usable, and how we can integrate pieces into our project.
â¸»
ðŸ” What I found: key features & patterns
AutoGen (Microsoft)
â€¢Â Â Â AutoGen is built for multi-agent conversation + orchestration. Agents can send messages, call tools, collaborate, or include human-in-the-loop.
â€¢Â Â Â It supports customizable agents: you can define agent behavior, tools, message formats.
â€¢Â Â Â Agents have .run(task) or .run_stream interfaces.
â€¢Â Â Â It includes a Core event-driven orchestration layer for distributed, long-running workflows.
â€¢Â Â Â They built AutoGen Studio, a no-code UI tool for prototyping/debugging agent workflows (drag-drop JSON specs) on top of AutoGen.
â€¢Â Â Â AutoGenâ€™s architecture is being revamped in v0.4 with an actor model (agents as actors sending messages) to improve modularity and scalability.
â€¢Â Â Â AutoGen supports integration with tools, distributed setups, human + AI agents.
Usable bits for us:
â€¢Â Â Â The .run(task) abstraction â€” easy interface to fire off an agent with a prompt.
â€¢Â Â Â The actor/message-based orchestration model.
â€¢Â Â Â Ability to integrate tools as functions agents can call.
â€¢Â Â Â The idea of â€œStudio / no-code JSON specâ€ for low friction prototyping â€” we could build a minimal version.
â¸»
LangChain
â€¢Â Â Â LangChain defines agents as systems using an LLM to decide which actions to take, i.e. the control flow is dynamic.
â€¢Â Â Â Agents in LangChain follow a loop:
1.	LLM picks an action (tool call)
2.	Execute the tool
3.	Get output
4.	Pass it back to LLM â†’ repeat or finish
â€¢Â Â Â Tools are external functions or APIs agents can call â€” search, calculators, custom logic, etc.
â€¢Â Â Â LangChain is modular: you can build custom tools, memory modules, prompting strategies.
â€¢Â Â Â They have an evolving subproject LangGraph aimed at more controllable and composable agent infrastructure.
â€¢Â Â Â They differentiate chains (hardcoded sequences) vs agents (dynamic decisions)
Usable bits for us:
â€¢Â Â Â The decision + tool + observation loop structure.
â€¢Â Â Â How to wrap arbitrary functions (tools) so the agent can call them.
â€¢Â Â Â Memory or state passing pattern â€” agents maintain context across steps.
â€¢Â Â Â Ability to mix and match agent styles (e.g. plan-and-execute, critique-revise).
â¸»
ðŸ§© What we can borrow / pull into our sandbox
Hereâ€™s how we can import and adapt useful parts into our minimal multi-agent framework:
Feature	What to import/adapt	How it would show in our code
Agent interface .run(task)	Use a base class Agent with .run(task) signature	class Agent: def run(self, task): ...
Decision loop (action â†’ observation â†’ next)	Build a loop inside agent	action = llm.decide(task), obs = tool(action), task = update_task(obs)
Tools abstraction	Wrap helper functions as tools that agents can call	tools = { "search": search_fn, "analyze": analyze_fn }
Messaging / orchestration between agents	Simple message queue / actor pattern	AgentA.send(task), AgentB.receive(...)
Human-in-the-loop / override	Allow tasks to pause and ask human input	if task.requires_confirmation: pause and return user input
JSON spec / configuration	A declarative file specifying agents, tools, and flows	agents.json â†’ load definitions into classes
Memory / state	Agent holds context in instance variables	self.memory = {...} persisted across run calls
â¸»
If you like, I can draft a minimal prototype file that fuses these bits (a skeleton agent + tool + messaging) so you can paste it into your repo and test. Do you want me to do that now?
Perfect â€” hereâ€™s a minimal prototype you can drop into your repo as agents.py.
It fuses the best ideas from AutoGen (agent .run(task), message passing) and LangChain (decision â†’ tool â†’ observation loop).
â¸»
agents.py
import json
import random
from typing import Dict, Any, Callable, List
class Agent:
def __init__(self, name: str, tools: Dict[str, Callable] = None):
self.name = name
self.tools = tools if tools else {}
self.memory: List[str] = []  # stores logs or state
def decide_action(self, task: str) -> str:
"""Fake decision-maker for now.
Later, plug in AI (GPT/Copilot) to choose tools intelligently."""
if not self.tools:
return "noop"
return random.choice(list(self.tools.keys()))
def run(self, task: str) -> Dict[str, Any]:
"""Core loop: pick a tool, run it, log result."""
action = self.decide_action(task)
if action in self.tools:
result = self.tools[action](task)
else:
result = f"No-op: {task}"
log = f"{self.name} ran {action} on task '{task}' â†’ {result}"
self.memory.append(log)
return {"agent": self.name, "action": action, "result": result}
def echo_tool(task: str) -> str:
return f"Echo: {task}"
def length_tool(task: str) -> str:
return f"Length={len(task)}"
def reverse_tool(task: str) -> str:
return task[::-1]
class Orchestrator:
def __init__(self, agents: List[Agent]):
self.agents = agents
self.ledger: List[Dict[str, Any]] = []
def broadcast(self, task: str):
"""Send the same task to all agents, collect results."""
for agent in self.agents:
result = agent.run(task)
self.ledger.append(result)
def save_ledger(self, path="ledger.json"):
with open(path, "w") as f:
json.dump(self.ledger, f, indent=2)
if __name__ == "__main__":
research_agent = Agent("ResearchAgent", {"echo": echo_tool, "length": length_tool})
audit_agent = Agent("AuditAgent", {"reverse": reverse_tool})
system = Orchestrator([research_agent, audit_agent])
system.broadcast("Find contradictions in Path.txt")
system.save_ledger()
print(json.dumps(system.ledger, indent=2))
â¸»
ðŸ§ª What this does
â€¢Â Â Â Defines a base Agent with .run(task) (like AutoGen).
â€¢Â Â Â Agents can call tools (here just toy functions: echo, length, reverse).
â€¢Â Â Â Agents store logs in memory.
â€¢Â Â Â An Orchestrator broadcasts tasks to all agents and writes results to a ledger.json.
â€¢Â Â Â Running the file will show a simple pipeline: task in â†’ agents act â†’ ledger out.
â¸»
