Perfect â€” hereâ€™s a README.md entry you can drop right into your repo (or append to your existing README). It frames the agents.py prototype in clear, professional terms so anyone landing on your GitHub sees what it is and why it matters.
â¸»
README.md
This repo contains an experimental prototype for **multi-agent systems** inspired by frameworks like [Microsoft AutoGen](https://github.com/microsoft/autogen) and [LangChain](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langchain).
The goal is to build a **lightweight, auditable sandbox** where autonomous agents can:
- Receive tasks
- Decide actions
- Call tools (functions/APIs)
- Log results into a shared ledger
- **Agent Class**:
Each agent has a `.run(task)` method and a small memory log.
- **Tool Integration**:
Tools are just Python functions wrapped so agents can call them. (Current demo tools: `echo`, `length`, `reverse`).
- **Orchestrator**:
Broadcasts tasks to multiple agents and collects results. Writes everything to a `ledger.json` file for auditing.
- **Ledger Output**:
All results are saved in structured JSON so workflows are transparent and reproducible.
python agents.py
Example Output:
[
{
"agent": "ResearchAgent",
"action": "length",
"result": "Length=33"
},
{
"agent": "AuditAgent",
"action": "reverse",
"result": "txt.htaP ni snoitcidercon dniF"
}
]
â¸»
Roadmap
â€¢Â Â Â Replace random action selection with AI decision-making (Copilot, GPT, Claude).
â€¢Â Â Â Add useful tools (file analyzers, contradiction finders, text classifiers).
â€¢Â Â Â Implement sequential workflows (Research â†’ Audit â†’ Implement).
â€¢Â Â Â Integrate with GitHub Actions for automated runs on commit.
â€¢Â Â Â Expand into human-in-the-loop agents (pause and request input).
â¸»
Why This Matters
This sandbox shows how autonomous agents can coordinate to metabolize contradictions, audit inputs, and act as a team.
Itâ€™s a practical, transparent starting point for experimenting with agent orchestration without the complexity of heavyweight frameworks.
