1. Update Workflow: .github/workflows/update_changelog.yml
name: Update Changelog
on:
push:
branches: [ "main" ]
jobs:
changelog:
runs-on: ubuntu-latest
steps:
- name: Checkout repository
uses: actions/checkout@v3
with:
fetch-depth: 0  # full history needed
- name: Set up Git
run: |
git config user.name "github-actions[bot]"
git config user.email "41898282+github-actions[bot]@users.noreply.github.com"
- name: Generate semantic changelog entry
run: |
COMMIT_MSG=$(git log -1 --pretty=format:"%s")
DATE=$(date -u +"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S UTC")
echo "## Commit on $DATE" > temp_changelog.md
echo "" >> temp_changelog.md
if [[ $COMMIT_MSG == feat:* ]]; then
echo "### Features" >> temp_changelog.md
elif [[ $COMMIT_MSG == fix:* ]]; then
echo "### Fixes" >> temp_changelog.md
elif [[ $COMMIT_MSG == chore:* ]]; then
echo "### Chores" >> temp_changelog.md
elif [[ $COMMIT_MSG == docs:* ]]; then
echo "### Documentation" >> temp_changelog.md
elif [[ $COMMIT_MSG == test:* ]]; then
echo "### Tests" >> temp_changelog.md
else
echo "### Other" >> temp_changelog.md
fi
echo "- $COMMIT_MSG" >> temp_changelog.md
echo "" >> temp_changelog.md
- name: Update CHANGELOG.md
run: |
cat temp_changelog.md CHANGELOG.md > NEW_CHANGELOG.md
mv NEW_CHANGELOG.md CHANGELOG.md
rm temp_changelog.md
- name: Commit updated changelog
run: |
git add CHANGELOG.md
git commit -m "chore: auto-update changelog with semantic commit"
git push
â¸»
2. Example Usage
If your commit message is:
git commit -m "feat: add contradiction detection tool"
The changelog will prepend:
- feat: add contradiction detection tool
If the commit was:
git commit -m "test: add pytest coverage for echo_tool"
The changelog gets:
- test: add pytest coverage for echo_tool
â¸»
ðŸ”‘ Why This Matters
â€¢Â Â Â Professional convention: semantic commits are standard in OSS and professional teams.
â€¢Â Â Â Structured changelog: easy to scan features vs fixes vs chores.
â€¢Â Â Â Automation discipline: ensures your public-facing Ledger always stays consistent with your commit style.
â¸»
ðŸ‘‰ From here, the last step is commit discipline: youâ€™ll want to always prefix commits with feat:, fix:, test:, docs:, or chore:.
Do you want me to also set up a commit linting GitHub Action that rejects non-semantic commit messages, so you never forget the format?
Exactly. A convention without enforcement slips fast â€” so letâ€™s close the loop with a commit linter that enforces semantic commit messages. This way, every commit that hits main will follow feat:, fix:, docs:, test:, or chore:.
â¸»
1. New Workflow: .github/workflows/commitlint.yml
name: Commit Lint
on:
push:
branches: [ "main" ]
pull_request:
branches: [ "main" ]
jobs:
lint-commits:
runs-on: ubuntu-latest
steps:
- name: Checkout repository
uses: actions/checkout@v3
with:
fetch-depth: 10  # check recent history
- name: Validate commit messages
run: |
PATTERN="^(feat|fix|docs|test|chore): .+"
git log -n 10 --pretty=format:"%s" | while read line; do
if ! [[ $line =~ $PATTERN ]]; then
echo "âŒ Commit message '$line' is invalid. Must start with feat:, fix:, docs:, test:, or chore:."
exit 1
fi
done
echo "âœ… All recent commit messages follow semantic convention."
â¸»
2. How It Works
â€¢Â Â Â On every push or PR:
â€¢Â Â Â Looks at the last 10 commit messages.
â€¢Â Â Â Ensures each starts with feat:, fix:, docs:, test:, or chore:.
â€¢Â Â Â Fails the workflow if any donâ€™t match.
â¸»
3. Example
âœ… Good commits:
