Got it. Hereâ€™s the upgrade: a GitHub Pages deployment step so your dashboard.html lives at a public URL, auto-updated on every push to main.

â¸»

.github/workflows/ci.yml (with Pages deploy)

name: Tessrax CI + Dashboard Deploy

on:
  push:
    branches: [ "main" ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ "main" ]

permissions:
  contents: write
  pages: write
  id-token: write

jobs:
  build-and-test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout repository
      uses: actions/checkout@v4

    - name: Set up Python
      uses: actions/setup-python@v5
      with:
        python-version: '3.11'

    - name: Install dependencies
      run: |
        python -m venv .venv
        source .venv/bin/activate
        pip install --upgrade pip
        pip install -r requirements.txt
        pip install pytest pytest-cov psutil

    - name: Run unit + integration tests
      run: |
        source .venv/bin/activate
        pytest --maxfail=1 --disable-warnings -q --cov=core --cov=compliance_auditor

    - name: Run stress tests and build dashboard
      run: |
        source .venv/bin/activate
        python ci_report.py

    - name: Upload dashboard artifact
      uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
      with:
        name: stress-dashboard
        path: dashboard.html

  deploy-pages:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: build-and-test
    steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4

    - name: Upload dashboard for Pages
      uses: actions/upload-pages-artifact@v3
      with:
        path: dashboard.html

    - name: Deploy to GitHub Pages
      id: deployment
      uses: actions/deploy-pages@v4


â¸»

What changes
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â New job deploy-pages runs after tests/stress harness succeed.
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â Uses upload-pages-artifact â†’ publishes dashboard.html.
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â Uses deploy-pages â†’ pushes it to GitHub Pages hosting.

â¸»

Result
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â CI still uploads the dashboard as a build artifact.
Â Â Â â€¢Â Â Â GitHub Pages also serves it live at:
https://<your-username>.github.io/<your-repo>/dashboard.html

(Replace <your-username> and <your-repo> with your GitHub info.)

